headline: European car sales rise 4.9% in October, ACEA says
summary:
STORY: New car sales in Europe rose 4.9% in October as electric cars outpaced petrol and diesel registrations.

Data from the European Automobile Manufacturers' Association showed on Tuesday (November 25) that sales in the EU, Britain and the European Free Trade Association rose to over a million cars.

Its largest markets including Germany and Britain added more new cars than last year.

The European car industry has taken a series of hits this year.

They include Donald Trump's trade tariffs, a slowdown in the Chinese market.

And a slower-than-expected transition to electric vehicles.

There have also been recent worries about a potential chip supply chain crisis surrounding Dutch chipmaker Nexperia.

Registrations at Volkswagen, Stellantis, rose year-on-year by 6.5% and 4.6% respectively, while Renault went up more than a tenth.

Tesla's sales meanwhile dropped almost by half from a year ago.

While BYD's sales jumped a near 207%.

And while electrics and hybrids saw a boost, all major markets saw drops in their petrol and diesel registrations.

headline: Tesla Had Another Bad Month in Europe
summary: Tesla’s European sales almost halved last month, undermining hopes that the revamped Model Y will revive the company’s fortunes in the region.  The electric-vehicle maker sold 6,964 cars in Europe in October, down from 13,519 in the same month last year, according to data released Tuesday by local trade body ACEA.  Year to date Tesla’s sales have fallen 30% in the region compared to the same period of 2024, despite a broader rebound in EV sales.

headline: Tesla Stock Could Hit $525, Analyst Says. Legacy Car Makers Can’t Think Like Startups.
summary: Tesla  stock dipped early Tuesday, after Monday’s huge gain, as car makers around the world weigh what autonomous driving technology means for their business. Melius Research analyst Rob Wertheimer wrote Monday that Tesla’s Full-Self Driving, or FSD, technology was improving rapidly and expanding its lead over the traditional car industry.
